<doc id="287775" wikidata="Q315057" url="?curid=287775" title="Koos (island)">
<text>Koos is the largest of several small islands in the Bay of Greifswald, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Germany. It has an area of 772 hectares and a maximum elevation of just above three meters. The island is a largely uninhabited natural reserve with restricted access. It is separated from the mainland by &quot;Kooser Bucht&quot; and &quot;Kooser See&quot;, two bays connected by a tiny strait, &quot;Beek&quot;.

In 1241, Barnuta, prince of Rügen, granted Koos (then &quot;&quot;Chosten&quot;) to Eldena abbey (then &quot;Hilda&quot;&quot;), later it became a possession of the Hanseatic town of Greifswald, located a few kilometers southward. A medieval burgh has been suggested on the isle, but not verified. A 17th-century Dutch settlement had disappeared in the 18th century. Koos is administered by the nearby town of Greifswald.

