<doc id="287808" wikidata="Q1495342" url="?curid=287808" title="Algebraic independence">
<text>In abstract algebra, a subset formula_1 of a field formula_2 is algebraically independent over a subfield formula_3 if the elements of formula_1 do not satisfy any non-trivial polynomial equation with coefficients in formula_3.

In particular, a one element set formula_6 is algebraically independent over formula_3 if and only if formula_8 is transcendental over formula_3. In general, all the elements of an algebraically independent set formula_1 over formula_3 are by necessity transcendental over formula_3, and over all of the field extensions over formula_3 generated by the remaining elements of formula_1.

==Example==
The real numbers formula_15 and formula_16 are transcendental numbers: they are not the roots of any nontrivial polynomial whose coefficients are rational numbers. Thus, the sets formula_17 and formula_18 are both algebraically independent over the rational numbers.

However, the set formula_19 is &quot;not&quot; algebraically independent over the rational numbers formula_20, because the nontrivial polynomial
:formula_21
is zero when formula_22 and formula_23.

==Algebraic independence of known constants==
Although  and  are transcendental, it is not known whether formula_24 is algebraically independent over formula_20. In fact, it is not even known whether formula_26 is irrational. Nesterenko proved in 1996 that:
* the numbers formula_27, formula_28, and formula_29, where formula_30 is the gamma function, are algebraically independent over formula_20;
* the numbers formula_32 and formula_33 are algebraically independent over formula_20;
* for all positive integers formula_35, the number formula_36 is algebraically independent over formula_20.

==Results and open problems==
The Lindemann–Weierstrass theorem can often be used to prove that some sets are algebraically independent over formula_20. It states that whenever formula_39 are algebraic numbers that are linearly independent over formula_20, then formula_41 are also algebraically independent over formula_20.

The Schanuel conjecture would establish the algebraic independence of many numbers, including &quot;&quot; and &quot;,&quot; but remains unproven:

:Let formula_43 be any set of formula_35 complex numbers that are linearly independent over formula_45. The field extension formula_46 has transcendence degree at least formula_35 over formula_45.

==Algebraic matroids==
Given a field extension formula_49 that is not algebraic, Zorn&#x27;s lemma can be used to show that there always exists a maximal algebraically independent subset of formula_2 over formula_3. Further, all the maximal algebraically independent subsets have the same cardinality, known as the transcendence degree of the extension.

For every finite set formula_1 of elements of formula_2, the algebraically independent subsets of formula_1 satisfy the axioms that define the independent sets of a matroid. In this matroid, the rank of a set of elements is its transcendence degree, and the flat generated by a set formula_55 of elements is the intersection of formula_2 with the field formula_57. A matroid that can be generated in this way is called an algebraic matroid. No good characterization of algebraic matroids is known, but certain matroids are known to be non-algebraic; the smallest is the Vámos matroid.

Many finite matroids may be represented by a matrix over a field formula_3, in which the matroid elements correspond to matrix columns, and a set of elements is independent if the corresponding set of columns is linearly independent. Every matroid with a linear representation of this type may also be represented as an algebraic matroid, by choosing an indeterminate for each row of the matrix, and by using the matrix coefficients within each column to assign each matroid element a linear combination of these transcendentals. The converse is false: not every algebraic matroid has a linear representation.

==See also==
*Linear independence
*Transcendental number
*Lindemann-Weierstrass theorem
*Schanuel&#x27;s conjecture
